Wash and dry produce.

Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2%units}, separating whites from greens. Thinly
slice half the @jalapeño{1%unit} into rounds; mince remaining. Dice
@roma tomato{1%unit}.

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon} in a large #pot{} over
medium-high heat. Add scallion whites and as much minced jalapeño as desired.
Season with @salt{}. Cook, stirring, until softened, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Add @ground pork{10%ounce} and @Southwest spice blend{2%tablespoon} to pot
with aromatics; season with salt and @pepper{}. Cook, breaking up meat into
pieces, until pork is browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Stir diced tomato, @Tex-Mex paste{1%unit}, and half the @crushed tomatoes{13.76%ounce} into
pot; cook until slightly darkened in color, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add @black beans{13.4%ounce} and their liquid, @chicken stock concentrate{2%units}, @water{1/4%cup}, salt, and pepper; stir to combine. Bring to a simmer and cook until thickened, ~{8-10%minutes}. Turn off heat. Taste and season with salt and pepper.

> If chili is too thick, add another splash of water.

Divide chili between bowls. Top with @smoky red pepper crema{2%tablespoon},
scallion greens, and as much sliced jalapeño as you like. Serve.

> A good chili has well-seasoned meat, creamy beans, and tender veggies.
> A great chili, however, has all that and comes together in one pot in under
> an hour. This chili is one of the greats. And once you take a bite, we can
> guarantee you'll agree.
